chapters_5to8 = {
    5: {'title': 'Safety Systems', 'subtitle': 'Redundancy, Emergency Landing, and Ballistic Parachutes', 'prev': 'chapter-04.html', 'next': 'chapter-06.html',
        'content': '<h2>🛡️ Safety is Paramount</h2><p>Aviation safety golden rule: "Less than 1 fatal accident per 10 million flight hours." This means 10^-7 level safety. For eVTOL to fly over countless people in cities, this safety level must be achieved - 10x safer than cars (10^-6) and 100x safer than general aviation (10^-5).</p><p>eVTOL achieves this through multiple layers of safety systems. Redundant/triplicated components, automatic fault detection and recovery, emergency landing systems, and ballistic parachutes as last resort - using Defense in Depth strategy.</p>' + '<h2>🔁 Redundancy</h2><h3>1. Propulsion System Redundancy</h3><p>eVTOLs biggest safety feature is distributed electric propulsion. Conventional helicopters have single main rotor and engine - engine failure is very dangerous (must autorotate to land). In contrast, eVTOL has multiple independent motors. Volocopter VoloCity has 18 motors - can safely land even if 9 fail. This is "50%+ failure tolerance" capability.</p>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>✅ Propulsion System Redundancy Levels</h4><ul><li><strong>N+1 Configuration:</strong> Tolerates 1 motor failure. Minimum requirement</li><li><strong>N+2 Configuration:</strong> Tolerates 2 simultaneous motor failures. Recommended level</li><li><strong>N/2 Configuration:</strong> Tolerates half of all motors failing. Highest level (Volocopter)</li></ul></div>' + '<h3>2. Battery Redundancy</h3><p>Battery packs also divided into multiple independent modules. Joby Aviation S4 has 12 independent battery modules, each managed by separate BMS. If one module fails or overheats, its automatically isolated and flight continues with remaining modules.</p><ul><li><strong>Module Isolation:</strong> Electrically disconnect failed module</li><li><strong>Thermal Isolation:</strong> Prevent one modules fire from spreading to others</li><li><strong>Power Redistribution:</strong> Prioritize critical systems with remaining modules</li></ul>' + '<h3>3. Flight Control Computer Redundancy</h3><p>As explained in previous chapter, eVTOL have 2 or 3 independent flight control computers. Sometimes using processors from different manufacturers to prevent Common Mode Failure.</p><h3>4. Sensor Redundancy</h3><p>All critical sensors installed in at least duplicate. IMU, GPS, barometer, magnetic compass all redundant, sometimes combining sensors of different principles (e.g., GPS + vision-based navigation).</p>' + '<h2>⚠️ Fault Detection and Management</h2><h3>1. Health Monitoring System</h3><p>eVTOL monitors all component status in real-time. Built-In Test (BIT) systems automatically check systems before, during, and after flight.</p><ul><li><strong>Motors:</strong> Monitor temperature, current, vibration, RPM deviation</li><li><strong>Batteries:</strong> Monitor cell-level voltage, temperature, internal resistance, swelling</li><li><strong>Control Surfaces:</strong> Compare commanded vs. actual position with position sensors</li><li><strong>Structure:</strong> Monitor structural fatigue with stress sensors</li></ul>' + '<h3>2. Predictive Maintenance</h3><p>Machine learning predicts component failures in advance. For example, detecting motor bearing vibration pattern changes allows replacement before failure.</p><h3>3. Automatic Fault Response</h3><p>When fault detected, system automatically responds: (1) Detect: Identify fault via sensors or self-diagnosis (2) Isolate: Isolate failed component from system (3) Reconfigure: Reconfigure with remaining systems (4) Degrade: Limit performance if necessary (speed reduction) (5) Land: Land at nearest safe location</p>' + '<h2>🪂 Emergency Landing Systems</h2><h3>1. Controlled Landing</h3><p>Even if some motors or batteries fail, attempt controlled landing with remaining systems. Flight control computer optimally distributes remaining thrust for safe touchdown.</p>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>🎯 Emergency Landing Priority</h4><ol><li><strong>1st Priority:</strong> Designated vertiports</li><li><strong>2nd Priority:</strong> Nearby airports or helipads</li><li><strong>3rd Priority:</strong> Large parking lots, parks, sports fields</li><li><strong>4th Priority:</strong> Roads (request traffic control)</li><li><strong>Last Resort:</strong> Water (passenger safety priority)</li></ol></div>' + '<h3>2. Autorotation (Tilt-Rotor eVTOL)</h3><p>Some tilt-rotor eVTOL designed to land via autorotation even with complete power loss. Propellers rotate from descending airflow to slow descent rate. However, this requires very skilled technique.</p><h3>3. Automatic Landing Site Selection</h3><p>AI system finds safe landing sites in real-time: Scan surrounding terrain with cameras and LiDAR. Identify flat surfaces, obstacle-free spaces. Prioritize areas without people or vehicles. Calculate optimal approach path considering wind direction and speed. Notify pilot or ground control of plan.</p>' + '<h2>🪂 Ballistic Recovery System (BRS)</h2><h3>1. Need for Parachute</h3><p>When all safety devices fail and aircraft becomes uncontrollable, last resort is lowering entire aircraft with parachute. Called Ballistic Recovery Systems (BRS) or Whole Aircraft Parachute System (WAPS). Already proven technology in small general aviation aircraft (Cirrus SR22, etc.), saving over 500 lives. Mandatory or strongly recommended for eVTOL.</p>' + '<h3>2. Operating Principle</h3><ol><li><strong>Deployment Decision:</strong> Pilot manually or system automatically decides parachute deployment</li><li><strong>Rocket Launch:</strong> Small solid rocket launches parachute above aircraft (within 1-2 seconds)</li><li><strong>Parachute Unfolds:</strong> Parachute fully unfolds in air (3-5 seconds)</li><li><strong>Descent:</strong> Entire aircraft suspended by parachute descends at 6-8 m/s</li><li><strong>Landing:</strong> Landing gear and shock absorption structure mitigate impact</li></ol>' + '<h3>3. Design Considerations</h3><ul><li><strong>Minimum Deployment Altitude:</strong> 100-150m AGL (Above Ground Level)</li><li><strong>Parachute Size:</strong> 2-3x aircraft weight area</li><li><strong>Descent Rate:</strong> 6-8 m/s (minimize passenger injury)</li><li><strong>Non-Reusable:</strong> Replace entire system after single use</li><li><strong>Weight:</strong> 3-5% of total aircraft weight</li></ul>' + '<p>Parachute is not panacea - insufficient deployment time below 100m, increased landing impact in strong winds (>25 kt), still dangerous over water or dense buildings, risk of entanglement with rotors/wings during deployment.</p>' + '<h2>🔥 Fire Prevention and Suppression</h2><h3>1. Battery Fire Risk</h3><p>Lithium-ion batteries have Thermal Runaway risk. If one cell overheats, internal chemical reactions can runaway causing fire and explosion.</p><h3>2. Fire Prevention Design</h3><ul><li><strong>Thermal Barriers Between Cells:</strong> Ceramic or aerogel insulation</li><li><strong>Pressure Relief:</strong> Safely vent gases when overheated</li><li><strong>Temperature Monitoring:</strong> Real-time cell-level temperature surveillance</li><li><strong>Current Limiting:</strong> Immediately cut overcurrent</li><li><strong>Mechanical Protection:</strong> Protect battery pack during collision</li></ul>' + '<h3>3. Fire Suppression System</h3><p>When fire occurs, suppression system automatically activates: Inject inert gas (nitrogen or CO2) to cut oxygen. Spray liquid coolant on hot cells. Isolate fire module electrically and thermally. Exhaust toxic gases outside aircraft.</p>' + '<h2>💺 Passenger Safety Equipment</h2><h3>1. Seat Belts and Crash Protection</h3><ul><li><strong>4-Point or 5-Point Harness:</strong> Secure shoulders and waist</li><li><strong>Airbags:</strong> Some eVTOL equipped with airbags (like cars)</li><li><strong>Energy-Absorbing Seats:</strong> Absorb downward impact energy</li><li><strong>Headrests:</strong> Prevent neck injury</li></ul>' + '<h3>2. Passenger Briefing</h3><p>Like commercial aircraft, eVTOL must provide passenger safety briefings: Seat belt usage. Emergency exit locations. Oxygen mask usage (if needed). Ditching procedures. Electronic device restrictions.</p>' + '<h2>🌊 Ditching Safety</h2><p>For routes over water, emergency ditching capability is important. Design considerations: Buoyancy - aircraft floats on water for period. Attitude stability - designed not to capsize. Escape routes - doors that open easily even on water. Life vests - at each seat. Emergency Position Indicating Radio Beacon - automatically activates on water contact to transmit position.</p>' + '<h2>📊 Achieving Safety Goals</h2><p>Through these multi-layer safety systems, eVTOL can achieve 10^-7 level safety goals. System safety analysis techniques (FTA, FMEA, FHA, etc.) identify all possible failure modes and prepare countermeasures.</p>' + '<div class="highlight"><h3>✅ Safety Design Principles</h3><ul><li><strong>Fail-Safe:</strong> Transition to safe state when failed</li><li><strong>Redundancy:</strong> Duplicate/triplicate critical systems</li><li><strong>Diversity:</strong> Combine different technologies to prevent common mode failures</li><li><strong>Defense in Depth:</strong> Multi-layer defense prevents single failure causing accident</li><li><strong>Safety by Design:</strong> Prioritize safety from design stage</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Next chapter examines the airworthiness certification process that officially verifies and certifies this safety.</p>'},
    
    6: {'title': 'Airworthiness Certification', 'subtitle': 'EASA SC-VTOL, FAA Part 23, Global Standards', 'prev': 'chapter-05.html', 'next': 'chapter-07.html',
        'content': '<h2>📜 What is Airworthiness Certification?</h2><p>Airworthiness Certification is the process where national aviation authorities officially recognize that aircraft can fly safely. Similar to automotive safety certification but far more stringent and comprehensive. Certifying a single aircraft takes years and costs hundreds of millions to billions of dollars.</p><p>eVTOL is entirely new aircraft category, so existing certification regulations cannot be directly applied. Therefore major aviation authorities like FAA (US Federal Aviation Administration), EASA (European Aviation Safety Agency), and CAAC (China Civil Aviation Administration) are developing eVTOL-specific certification standards.</p>' + '<h2>🌍 Major Certification Authorities and Standards</h2><h3>1. FAA (US Federal Aviation Administration)</h3><p>FAA classifies eVTOL as "Powered Lift" category. Neither conventional helicopter nor fixed-wing - entirely new category. FAA issues Special Conditions for eVTOL based on existing Part 23 (small aircraft) standards.</p>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>✈️ FAA eVTOL Certification Path</h4><ul><li><strong>Part 23:</strong> Small aircraft airworthiness standards (basic framework)</li><li><strong>Special Conditions:</strong> Additional requirements for eVTOL-specific characteristics</li><li><strong>Type Certification:</strong> Aircraft design certification (TC)</li><li><strong>Production Certification:</strong> Manufacturing process certification (PC)</li><li><strong>Airworthiness Certificate:</strong> Individual aircraft airworthiness certificate</li></ul></div>' + '<h3>2. EASA (European Aviation Safety Agency)</h3><p>EASA issued "Special Condition for VTOL" (SC-VTOL) in 2019. First comprehensive certification standard written specifically for eVTOL. SC-VTOL divides into Enhanced Category (EC) or Basic Category (BC).</p><ul><li><strong>Basic Category:</strong> 2 passengers or less, simple eVTOL (e.g., personal recreational)</li><li><strong>Enhanced Category:</strong> Commercial operation eVTOL, stricter standards</li></ul>' + '<h3>3. CAAC (China Civil Aviation Administration)</h3><p>China is moving fast on eVTOL certification. EHang EH216 obtained worlds first Type Certificate from CAAC in 2021. China is streamlining certification procedures to foster domestic UAM industry.</p>' + '<h3>4. Korean Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport</h3><p>Korea is developing own eVTOL certification standards as part of K-UAM initiative. Referencing FAA and EASA standards but including additional requirements for Koreas high-density urban environment. Collaborating with domestic manufacturers like Hyundai Supernal to establish certification system targeting 2025 commercialization.</p>' + '<h2>📋 Type Certification Process</h2><h3>5-Stage Certification Process</h3><p>FAA and EASA use similar 5-stage certification processes. Explained using Joby Aviations case.</p>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>Stage 1: Certification Basis Definition</h4><p>Manufacturer and authority cooperate to define specific certification standards for the aircraft. Agree on which regulations (Part 23, Special Conditions, etc.) to apply and how.</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> 6-12 months</p></div>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>Stage 2: Means of Compliance</h4><p>Manufacturer presents how to meet each certification requirement. Documents specific verification methods like testing, analysis, simulation.</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> 12-18 months</p></div>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>Stage 3: Compliance Verification</h4><p>Actually perform tests and analyses to prove aircraft meets requirements. Includes ground testing, flight testing, system safety analysis.</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> 24-36 months</p></div>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>Stage 4: Certification Plan Approval</h4><p>Authority reviews and approves manufacturers certification plan. Reviews all documents, test results, analysis reports.</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> 6-12 months</p></div>' + '<div class="tech-box"><h4>Stage 5: Type Certificate Issuance</h4><p>When all requirements met, issues Type Certificate (TC). Can now produce and sell aircraft of that design.</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> 3-6 months</p></div>' + '<p><strong>Total Duration:</strong> Average 5-7 years. <strong>Cost:</strong> Small eVTOL $100M-500M, Large $500M-2B</p>' + '<h2>🧪 Certification Test Items</h2><h3>1. Ground Testing</h3><ul><li><strong>Static Structural Test:</strong> Apply extreme loads to wings, fuselage for destructive testing</li><li><strong>Fatigue Test:</strong> Verify long-term durability with tens of thousands of repeated loads</li><li><strong>Crash Test:</strong> Landing gear and shock absorption performance testing</li><li><strong>Battery Safety Test:</strong> Overcharge, nail penetration, fire, crash testing</li><li><strong>Electromagnetic Compatibility (EMC):</strong> Resistance to lightning, radio interference</li><li><strong>Noise Measurement:</strong> Measure noise levels during take-off/landing and cruise</li></ul>' + '<h3>2. Flight Testing</h3><p>Hundreds of hours of flight testing to verify aircraft flight characteristics:</p><ul><li><strong>Performance Testing:</strong> Top speed, climb rate, range, ceiling</li><li><strong>Handling and Stability:</strong> Control response at various speeds and weights</li><li><strong>Transition Testing:</strong> Vertical to horizontal flight transition (tilt-rotor)</li><li><strong>Failure Mode Testing:</strong> Flight capability with 1-2 motor failures</li><li><strong>Autonomous Flight Testing:</strong> Autonomous flight system accuracy and safety</li><li><strong>Extreme Environment Testing:</strong> High/low temperature, strong wind, rain, icing conditions</li></ul>' + '<h3>3. System Safety Analysis</h3><ul><li><strong>FHA (Functional Hazard Assessment):</strong> Assess functional failure hazards</li><li><strong>FTA (Fault Tree Analysis):</strong> Analyze failure combinations leading to accidents</li><li><strong>FMEA (Failure Modes and Effects Analysis):</strong> Analyze each component failure effects</li><li><strong>PSSA (Preliminary System Safety Assessment):</strong> Design stage safety assessment</li><li><strong>SSA (System Safety Assessment):</strong> Final system safety verification</li></ul>' + '<h2>🔊 Noise Certification</h2><p>For eVTOL to operate in cities, noise must be low. Must comply with ICAO Annex 16 and each countrys noise regulations.</p>' + '<div class="highlight"><h3>🔉 eVTOL Noise Standards</h3><ul><li><strong>Take-Off/Landing:</strong> Maximum 65 dB @ 100m distance</li><li><strong>Cruise:</strong> Maximum 60 dB @ 100m distance</li><li><strong>Ground Operations:</strong> Maximum 70 dB @ vertiport boundary</li><li><strong>Night Operations:</strong> Additional 5-10 dB restriction (varies by region)</li></ul></div>' + '<p>For reference, normal conversation is 60 dB, helicopters 90-105 dB. eVTOL is 30-45 dB quieter than helicopters at "acceptable in cities" level.</p>' + '<h2>🏭 Production Certification</h2><p>Type Certification is approval of "design". Actually producing aircraft requires separate Production Certificate (PC). This proves manufacturers quality management system can consistently produce aircraft per certified design.</p>' + '<h3>Production Certification Requirements</h3><ul><li><strong>Quality Management System:</strong> ISO 9001 or AS9100 certification</li><li><strong>Process Documentation:</strong> Detailed procedures for all manufacturing processes</li><li><strong>Inspection and Testing:</strong> Component and system inspection for each aircraft</li><li><strong>Supply Chain Management:</strong> Subcontractor quality assurance</li><li><strong>Traceability:</strong> Track origin and history of each part</li><li><strong>Nonconformance Management:</strong> Procedures for isolating and handling defective parts</li></ul>' + '<h2>📄 Continuing Airworthiness</h2><p>Even after certification, must maintain aircraft safety. Called Continuing Airworthiness.</p>' + '<h3>1. Maintenance Program</h3><ul><li><strong>Daily Check:</strong> Pre-flight visual inspection, system self-diagnosis</li><li><strong>Weekly Check:</strong> Battery status, motor vibration, hydraulic/cooling systems</li><li><strong>Monthly Check:</strong> Comprehensive system check, software updates</li><li><strong>Annual Maintenance:</strong> Major component replacement, structural inspection, performance testing</li></ul>' + '<h3>2. Airworthiness Directives (AD)</h3><p>When safety issues discovered during operations, aviation authorities issue Airworthiness Directives. All operators must immediately comply. For example, if fire risk found in specific battery model, AD issued to immediately replace those batteries.</p>' + '<h3>3. Service Bulletins</h3><p>Improvements voluntarily issued by manufacturers. Not mandatory but recommended. Examples include new software updates or improved components.</p>' + '<h2>🌐 International Mutual Recognition</h2><p>eVTOL manufacturers want to operate in multiple countries. Certifying separately in each country takes too much time and money. Therefore mutual recognition agreements between major aviation authorities are important.</p><ul><li><strong>BASA (Bilateral Aviation Safety Agreement):</strong> Bilateral safety agreements</li><li><strong>FAA-EASA Agreement:</strong> US-Europe certification mutual recognition</li><li><strong>ICAO Standards:</strong> International Civil Aviation Organizations global standards</li></ul>' + '<p>Currently eVTOL lacks complete mutual recognition. Each authority conducts own review but references other authorities test data to reduce duplication.</p>' + '<h2>📊 Major eVTOL Certification Status (as of 2024)</h2><ul><li><strong>EHang EH216:</strong> CAAC Type Certificate obtained (2021), commercial operations in China</li><li><strong>Joby Aviation S4:</strong> Passed FAA Stage 4 of 5, targeting 2025 certification</li><li><strong>Volocopter VoloCity:</strong> EASA SC-VTOL certification in progress, expecting 2024-2025</li><li><strong>Lilium Jet:</strong> Early EASA certification stage, targeting 2026</li><li><strong>Archer Maker:</strong> Early FAA stage, targeting 2025-2026</li><li><strong>Wisk Aero 6th Gen:</strong> Negotiating FAA autonomous flight certification path</li></ul>' + '<p>Next chapter examines major manufacturers developing these eVTOL in detail.</p>'},
    
    7: {'title': 'eVTOL Manufacturers', 'subtitle': 'Leading Companies and Their Aircraft', 'prev': 'chapter-06.html', 'next': 'chapter-08.html',
        'content': '<h2>🏭 eVTOL Industry Ecosystem</h2><p>As of 2024, over 700 eVTOL projects worldwide. About 50 manufacturers have built actual flyable prototypes, and a dozen companies are seriously pursuing certification. This chapter examines major eVTOL manufacturers leading the industry.</p>' + '<h2>🇺🇸 US Manufacturers</h2><h3>1. Joby Aviation</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2009 (Santa Cruz, California)<br><strong>Founder:</strong> JoeBen Bevirt<br><strong>IPO:</strong> 2021 NYSE (Ticker: JOBY), Market cap ~$5B<br><strong>Total Funding:</strong> Over $2B<br><strong>Major Investors:</strong> Toyota, Uber, Intel, Baillie Gifford</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>Joby S4 Specifications</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Tilt-rotor (6 propellers)</li><li>Passengers: 4 + 1 pilot</li><li>Top Speed: 320 km/h</li><li>Range: 240 km</li><li>Maximum Altitude: 4,600m</li><li>Noise: 65 dB @ 100m (takeoff/landing), 45 dB @ 100m (cruise)</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Joby currently leads the eVTOL industry. Passed FAA Stage 4 of 5 certification, targeting 2025 commercial operations. Acquired Uber Elevate in 2020 to secure air taxi platform. Closely collaborating with Toyota to prepare mass production, planning to start production at California Marina factory from 2024.</p>' + '<p>Jobys strength is outstanding performance. 320 km/h speed and 240km range are top among current eVTOL in development. Very low noise suitable for urban operations. Especially 45 dB cruise noise is quiet enough to blend with ambient noise.</p>' + '<h3>2. Archer Aviation</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2018 (Palo Alto, California)<br><strong>Founders:</strong> Brett Adcock, Adam Goldstein<br><strong>IPO:</strong> 2021 NYSE (Ticker: ACHR)<br><strong>Total Funding:</strong> $1.5B<br><strong>Major Investors:</strong> United Airlines, Stellantis</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>Archer Midnight Specifications</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Lift+Cruise (12 lift rotors + 6 tilting propellers)</li><li>Passengers: 4 + 1 pilot</li><li>Top Speed: 240 km/h</li><li>Range: 160 km</li><li>Charging Time: 10 minutes (optimized for continuous operations)</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Archer especially emphasizes fast turnaround time. Can fly again after 10-minute charge for multiple daily flights. Signed $1 billion contract with United Airlines, planning Newark Airport to Manhattan air taxi route.</p>' + '<h3>3. Wisk Aero</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2019 (Boeing + Kitty Hawk joint venture)<br><strong>Headquarters:</strong> Mountain View, California<br><strong>Owner:</strong> Boeing 100% (acquired Kitty Hawk 2022)<br><strong>Investment:</strong> Full Boeing support</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>Wisk 6th Generation Specifications</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Lift+Cruise (12 lift rotors + 4 pusher propellers)</li><li>Passengers: 4 (no pilot - fully autonomous)</li><li>Top Speed: 220 km/h</li><li>Range: 140 km</li><li>Feature: Worlds first unmanned air taxi target</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Wisks biggest differentiator is fully autonomous flight. Operating without pilots reduces operating costs and increases safety (eliminates human error). Leveraging Boeings aviation expertise and capital, working closely with FAA to pioneer autonomous eVTOL certification paths.</p>' + '<h2>🇩🇪 German Manufacturers</h2><h3>4. Volocopter</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2011 (Bruchsal, Germany)<br><strong>Founders:</strong> Stephan Wolf, Alexander Zosel<br><strong>Total Funding:</strong> $500M<br><strong>Major Investors:</strong> Daimler, Intel, Geely</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>Volocopter VoloCity Specifications</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Multicopter (18 fixed rotors)</li><li>Passengers: 1 + 1 pilot</li><li>Top Speed: 110 km/h</li><li>Range: 35 km</li><li>Feature: Worlds first manned electric multicopter (2013)</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Volocopter is eVTOL pioneer. Achieved worlds first manned electric multicopter flight in 2011, planning demonstration operations at 2024 Paris Olympics. EASA SC-VTOL certification in progress - likely first commercial in Europe. Specialized for short distances - optimal for 5-15km urban trips. 18 rotors high redundancy for very safe, low noise suitable for city operations.</p>' + '<h3>5. Lilium</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2015 (Munich, Germany)<br><strong>Founders:</strong> Daniel Wiegand, Sebastian Born, Patrick Nathen, Matthias Meiner<br><strong>IPO:</strong> 2021 NASDAQ (Ticker: LILM)<br><strong>Total Funding:</strong> $1B</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>Lilium Jet Specifications</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Ducted fan tilting (36 electric jet engines)</li><li>Passengers: 6 + 1 pilot</li><li>Top Speed: 280 km/h</li><li>Range: 250 km</li><li>Feature: Unique ducted fan technology</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Lilium uses unique electric ducted fan technology. 36 small jet engines embedded in wings tilt to generate vertical lift and forward thrust. High speed and long range suitable for intercity travel. Building large-scale production facilities in Florida and Germany.</p>' + '<h2>🇨🇳 Chinese Manufacturers</h2><h3>6. EHang</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2014 (Guangzhou, China)<br><strong>Founder:</strong> Huazhi Hu<br><strong>IPO:</strong> 2019 NASDAQ (Ticker: EH)<br><strong>Type Certificate:</strong> 2021 CAAC (worlds first)</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>EHang EH216 Specifications</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Multicopter (16 rotors)</li><li>Passengers: 2 (no pilot - fully autonomous)</li><li>Top Speed: 130 km/h</li><li>Range: 30 km</li><li>Feature: Worlds first Type Certified eVTOL</li></ul></div>' + '<p>EHang obtained worlds first eVTOL Type Certificate from CAAC in 2021. Designed for fully autonomous operation without pilots, already demonstrating commercial operations in China, Dubai, and Spain. Rapidly commercializing with strong Chinese government support.</p>' + '<h2>🇰🇷 Korean Manufacturers</h2><h3>7. Hyundai Supernal</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2020 (Hyundai Motor Group)<br><strong>Headquarters:</strong> Washington DC, USA<br><strong>Investment:</strong> Full Hyundai Motor Group support<br><strong>Target:</strong> 2028 commercialization</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>Supernal S-A2 Specifications (Expected)</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Tilt-rotor</li><li>Passengers: 4-5</li><li>Top Speed: 240+ km/h</li><li>Range: 100+ km</li><li>Feature: Leveraging Hyundais mass production expertise</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Hyundai Supernal leads Korean eVTOL development. Utilizing Hyundai Motor Groups automotive manufacturing experience and electric vehicle technology to target stable, affordable eVTOL. FAA certification in progress, closely collaborating with Korean governments K-UAM initiative. Hyundai produces millions of cars annually - mass production capability expected to play important role in popularizing eVTOL. Plan to rapidly increase production after 2028 commercialization to reduce prices.</p>' + '<h2>🇬🇧 UK Manufacturers</h2><h3>8. Vertical Aerospace</h3><div class="company-card"><h4>🚁 Company Overview</h4><p><strong>Founded:</strong> 2016 (Bristol, UK)<br><strong>Founder:</strong> Stephen Fitzpatrick<br><strong>IPO:</strong> 2021 NYSE (Ticker: EVTL)<br><strong>Major Customers:</strong> American Airlines, Virgin Atlantic, Avolon</p></div>' + '<div class="spec-table"><p><strong>Vertical VX4 Specifications</strong></p><ul><li>Design Type: Lift+Cruise (8 lift rotors + 4 tilting propellers)</li><li>Passengers: 4 + 1 pilot</li><li>Top Speed: 320 km/h</li><li>Range: 160 km</li><li>Feature: Europes largest eVTOL pre-orders</li></ul></div>' + '<p>Vertical Aerospace secured over 1,400 pre-orders including American Airlines (250), Virgin Atlantic (150), Avolon (500). Closely collaborating with UK government to make London an eVTOL hub.</p>' + '<h2>📊 Manufacturer Comparison</h2><div class="highlight"><h3>🏆 Each Manufacturers Strengths</h3><ul><li><strong>Joby:</strong> Best performance (speed, range), certification progress #1</li><li><strong>Archer:</strong> Fast turnaround, major airline partnerships</li><li><strong>Wisk:</strong> Autonomous flight leader, Boeing support</li><li><strong>Volocopter:</strong> Longest experience, European market leader</li><li><strong>Lilium:</strong> Unique technology, long-range operations</li><li><strong>EHang:</strong> Worlds first certification, rapid commercialization</li><li><strong>Supernal:</strong> Mass production capability, automotive technology utilization</li><li><strong>Vertical:</strong> Large-scale pre-orders, airline partnerships</li></ul></div>' + '<h2>🌐 Global Competition Landscape</h2><p>eVTOL industry currently US-led. Most major players are American companies like Joby, Archer, Wisk, Beta Technologies, with over 70% of total investment concentrated in US companies. Europe has strong technical capabilities but relatively less capital. Volocopter and Lilium lead with EASAs systematic certification framework (SC-VTOL) as strength. China rapidly catching up government-led. EHang obtained worlds first certification, followers like AutoFlight, XPeng HT also growing fast. Chinese market scale and government support are strengths. Korea pursuing technology independence through Hyundai and Hanwhas eVTOL development, building infrastructure and systems together with K-UAM initiative. Planning technology validation through 2025 K-UAM Grand Challenge.</p>' + '<p>Next chapter examines eVTOL future - market outlook, technology roadmap, and development direction to 2050.</p>'},
    
    8: {'title': 'Future of eVTOL', 'subtitle': 'Market Outlook and Technology Roadmap', 'prev': 'chapter-07.html', 'next': '../ko/index.html',
        'content': '<h2>🚀 eVTOL Market Outlook</h2><p>eVTOL will be one of the 21st centurys most revolutionary transport innovations. Multiple market research agencies predict explosive growth of eVTOL and UAM markets.</p>' + '<h3>Major Market Research Results</h3><div class="highlight"><h4>💰 Global eVTOL/UAM Market Size Projections</h4><ul><li><strong>Morgan Stanley (2020):</strong> $1.5T by 2040 (Air taxi $850B, Cargo $650B)</li><li><strong>Roland Berger (2023):</strong> $90B by 2050 (2.3B annual passengers)</li><li><strong>McKinsey (2022):</strong> $500B by 2035 (cumulative market size)</li><li><strong>ARK Invest (2023):</strong> $800B by 2030 (including autonomous flight)</li></ul></div>' + '<p>For these projections to realize, several prerequisites needed: Continued battery technology advances, large-scale certification completion, vertiport infrastructure construction, regulatory framework establishment, public acceptance.</p>' + '<h2>📅 Technology Roadmap (2025-2050)</h2><div class="timeline-future"><div class="timeline-future-item"><h4>2025-2027: Initial Commercialization</h4><ul><li>Joby, Archer, Volocopter, etc. first commercial services start</li><li>Airport shuttle routes focus (city-airport)</li><li>Pilot onboard, limited autonomous functions</li><li>Price: $5-8 per mile (premium service)</li><li>Battery: 250-300 Wh/kg, range 50-250km</li><li>50-100 vertiports operating worldwide</li><li>Annual passengers: 1 million</li></ul></div>' + '<div class="timeline-future-item"><h4>2028-2030: Growth and Expansion</h4><ul><li>Add short-range urban routes</li><li>Partial autonomous flight (Level 3) introduction</li><li>Price: $3-5 per mile (middle class accessible)</li><li>Battery: 350-400 Wh/kg (early solid-state)</li><li>Range: 300-400km</li><li>Vertiports: 500-1,000 (major cities)</li><li>Annual passengers: 150 million</li><li>Cargo eVTOL full operations (medical, urgent delivery)</li></ul></div>' + '<div class="timeline-future-item"><h4>2031-2035: Popularization</h4><ul><li>Fully autonomous flight (Level 4-5) commercialization</li><li>Price: $2-4 per mile (public transport competitive)</li><li>Battery: 450-500 Wh/kg (solid-state mainstream)</li><li>Range: 500-700km</li><li>Vertiports: 5,000-10,000 (worldwide)</li><li>Annual passengers: 1.5 billion</li><li>Scheduled route operations (timetable-based like subway)</li><li>Fully integrated MaaS (seamless connection with ground transport)</li></ul></div>' + '<div class="timeline-future-item"><h4>2036-2040: Maturity Stage</h4><ul><li>Partial replacement of domestic flights (within 500km)</li><li>Price: $1-2 per mile (bus/subway level)</li><li>Hydrogen fuel cell eVTOL introduction (1,000km+ range)</li><li>Battery: 600+ Wh/kg (lithium-sulfur, lithium-air)</li><li>Vertiports: 50,000 (including mid-size cities)</li><li>Annual passengers: 2.3 billion</li><li>Total transport modal share: 5-10%</li><li>Carbon neutrality achieved (renewable energy charging)</li></ul></div>' + '<div class="timeline-future-item"><h4>2041-2050: Continued Innovation</h4><ul><li>Personal eVTOL ownership spreads (like cars)</li><li>Ultra-high-speed eVTOL (500+ km/h, tilt-wing or compound designs)</li><li>Complete noise elimination technology (below 50 dB)</li><li>Brain-computer interface control</li><li>Urban 3D traffic network completion (altitude-based layers)</li><li>Integration with space tourism (ground-space integrated transport)</li></ul></div></div>' + '<h2>🔬 Next-Generation Technologies</h2><h3>1. Battery Technology Innovation</h3><p>eVTOL future depends on battery technology. From current 250-300 Wh/kg, targeting 500 Wh/kg by 2030s, 1,000 Wh/kg by 2040s.</p><ul><li><strong>Solid-State Batteries (2028~):</strong> 400-500 Wh/kg, 1/5 charging time, zero fire risk</li><li><strong>Lithium-Sulfur Batteries (2032~):</strong> 600-800 Wh/kg, low cost</li><li><strong>Lithium-Air Batteries (2040~):</strong> 1,000+ Wh/kg, theoretical limit</li><li><strong>Graphene Batteries (research):</strong> Ultra-fast charging, long life</li></ul>' + '<h3>2. Hydrogen Fuel Cells</h3><p>For long-range operations (500km+), hydrogen fuel cell eVTOL will be developed. Hydrogen has much higher energy density per weight than batteries - suitable for long distances.</p><ul><li><strong>H2FLY (Germany):</strong> Developing hydrogen fuel cell aircraft</li><li><strong>ZeroAvia (UK/US):</strong> Hydrogen electric propulsion systems</li><li><strong>Hyundai:</strong> Hydrogen eVTOL research (utilizing automotive hydrogen technology)</li></ul>' + '<h3>3. Fully Autonomous Flight</h3><p>By 2030s, pilotless fully autonomous flight will become mainstream. AI handles all flight phases, ground control monitors dozens to hundreds simultaneously.</p><ul><li>Computer vision for obstacle recognition</li><li>Deep learning for real-time optimal path calculation</li><li>5G/6G networks for ultra-low latency communication</li><li>Digital twin for simulation-based safety verification</li></ul>' + '<h3>4. 3D Altitude Traffic Network</h3><p>Divide urban airspace into multiple altitudes for efficient utilization:</p><ul><li><strong>300-500m:</strong> Low-speed multicopters (tourism, short-range)</li><li><strong>500-1,000m:</strong> Medium-speed air taxis (urban travel)</li><li><strong>1,000-1,500m:</strong> High-speed tilt-rotors (long-range)</li><li><strong>1,500-3,000m:</strong> Cargo and special missions</li></ul>' + '<h2>🌏 Social Impact</h2><h3>1. Urban Planning Changes</h3><p>eVTOL will change cities physical structure. Vertiports installed on all major building rooftops, parking lots converted to charging stations. Cities expand vertically not horizontally, movement between high-rise buildings becomes very fast.</p>' + '<h3>2. Economic Impact</h3><p>New jobs created: eVTOL manufacturing, vertiport operations, maintenance, air traffic control, software development, battery manufacturing, infrastructure construction. McKinsey predicts over 1 million jobs globally by 2040.</p>' + '<h3>3. Environmental Benefits</h3><p>Ground traffic reduction improves urban air quality. Charging with renewable energy significantly reduces carbon emissions. Also, no road expansion needed preserves green spaces.</p>' + '<h3>4. Equity and Accessibility</h3><p>Initially premium service but by 2030s price will drop to public transport level. Island regions, mountainous areas, developing nations with inadequate infrastructure will greatly benefit.</p>' + '<h2>⚠️ Challenges</h2><h3>1. Technical Challenges</h3><ul><li>Battery energy density improvement (still 1/40 of jet fuel)</li><li>Large-scale charging infrastructure construction</li><li>Overcoming weather constraints (icing, strong winds, lightning)</li><li>Cybersecurity (hack prevention)</li></ul>' + '<h3>2. Regulatory and Policy</h3><ul><li>International standardization (mutual recognition between countries)</li><li>Airspace management (coexistence with existing aircraft)</li><li>Noise regulations (resident acceptance)</li><li>Privacy protection (flight data, passenger information)</li></ul>' + '<h3>3. Social Acceptance</h3><ul><li>Public safety perception (major impact from initial accidents)</li><li>Privacy concerns (looking down from sky)</li><li>Equity issues (concern about wealthy-only service)</li></ul>' + '<div class="vision-box"><h3>✨ The 2050 eVTOL World</h3><p>In 2050, you summon an eVTOL with your smartphone in the morning. 5 minutes later, with quiet humming, an eVTOL lands on your apartment rooftop vertiport. When you board, the door closes and automatically takes off. There is no pilot. AI controls everything.</p><p>Outside the window you see hundreds of eVTOL flying orderly at their respective altitudes. Like a 3D highway. 20 minutes later you arrive at your office building rooftop 60km away. A distance that would take 2 hours on the ground, in 20 minutes without traffic.</p><p>In the afternoon you travel with a friend to a coastal city. 250km in 1 hour, have lunch, enjoy the afternoon, and return home for dinner. The cost is slightly more than high-speed rail. eVTOL has become routine transportation like buses or subways.</p><p>The sky is no longer just for airplanes. Its everyones travel space. Traffic congestion is a thing of the past, cities are cleaner and quieter, and people travel farther, more frequently, and more easily.</p><p style="text-align: center; margin-top: 30px; font-size: 1.3em; color: #e94560;"><strong>This is the future eVTOL promises.</strong></p></div>' + '<h2>🎯 Conclusion</h2><p>eVTOL is not just a new vehicle. Its an innovation that will change urban transport paradigm, redefine city planning, and greatly improve peoples quality of life. When first commercial services start in 2025, it will grow explosively over the next 25 years to become mainstream transport used by billions annually by 2050. Many challenges remain - battery technology, autonomous flight, infrastructure construction - but industry and government are actively solving them one by one.</p><p>Humanity is once again making sky dreams reality 120 years after the Wright brothers. This time, its sky for everyone. The age of eVTOL is coming.</p>' + '<div class="highlight"><h4>🚁 WIA-SPACE-019 eVTOL Standard Conclusion</h4><p>We hope this standard document helps understand eVTOL technology, contribute to industry development, and create a better future.</p><p style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px; font-size: 1.2em; color: #e94560;"><strong>弘益人間 (Hongik Ingan) - Benefit All Humanity</strong></p></div>'}
}

